## To meet point 5 of the Service Standard

User researchers must:

- consider how people will use the service with assistive technology such as
 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/technology/testing-with-assistive-technologies" target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">screen readers, speech recognition software and magnifiers (opens in new tab)</a> 
- research with participants with access needs to be aware of the types of users you may need to test with in alpha
- not rely solely on external accessibility audits, for example <a href="https://digitalaccessibilitycentre.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopner noreferrer">Digital Accessibility Centre (DAC) (opens in new tab)</a> audits 
- demonstrate a good sample of users from realistic user groups
- engage stakeholders early on and advocate for designing an accessible service in future phases

### How you'll be assessed on this

At a discovery assessment assessors will look for:

- enough research with target users has been carried out
- decisions made on research observations and user needs
- the team's understanding of accessibility and assisted digital needs
- how the team plans to recruit participants with access needs to test any prototypes in alpha

